    <p>The Fram Museum is built around the polar vessel Fram — the strongest wooden ship ever constructed. Launched in 1892, Fram was used on three major polar expeditions: Fridtjof Nansen's Arctic drift in 1893–96, Otto Sverdrup's Canadian Arctic expedition in 1898–1902, and Roald Amundsen's Antarctic expedition in 1910–12, during which his team became the first to reach the South Pole. Fram sailed further north and further south than any other wooden vessel in history. Visitors can board the ship and walk through the cabins, lounges, cargo hold, and engine room.</p>
    <p>Also on display is the Gjøa, the ship Roald Amundsen commanded during the first successful navigation of the Northwest Passage (1903–06). The museum features the N25 polar flight 4D cinema and a simulator that recreates storm conditions at sea. Educational texts are available in 10 languages throughout. The Framheim Café and a gift shop with books and polar merchandise are on site. Wheelchair access is available via a lift and stair lift.</p>
    <p>The museum is located at Bygdøynesveien 39 on the Bygdøy Peninsula, within walking distance of the Kon-Tiki Museum and the Norwegian Maritime Museum. Combined tickets for two or all three museums are available on-site at any of the three locations — not online. The museum is open every day of the year; no advance booking required. Free entry with Oslo Pass.<br/><em style="font-size:.68rem;color:var(--dim)">Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</em></p>
